This output will focus on two working days (the format of the sessions will be confirmed later during Q3). It aims to target 200 academics, and the training will be provided in four modules and four locations. The modules will be the following:
1. Products, technologies, charging infrastructure; 
2. Best practices in regulation of operations and financing options; 
3. Private operations service providers and their preferred business models; 
4. Lessons from the existing RFPs, O&M, Concession Agreements, Escrows and Conditions Precedents.

This output aims to provide EV charger host locations and set up real-time communication with the utility’s distribution management system. This will demonstrate usefulness and relevance for beneficiaries by ensuring the following criteria when setting up and running the pilot: 
1) the technology implemented is open, cost-effective, and easy to deploy for a large number of utilities and charging network operator customers; 
2) work with BYPL (electric utility company) to list a wide range of common grid scenarios under which to test the pilot implementation; 
3) engage electric vehicle network users and clients to capture their feedback and inputs on what works, and does not work, when participating in a utility led demand response initiative.
In addition, this output will determine potential savings and environmental impact. Suitable host sites will be jointly identified by BYPL and eDRV’s technical team. The findings and recommendations of the demonstration activities will be summarised and delivered as a pdf document.

The governance structure is fundamental to the sustainability and replicability of the fundraising strategy. The governance structure will institutionalise future GB emissions and internal processes. It will be led by MEF with support from MINAM and participation by key relevant ministries when relevant (to be confirmed) and be responsible for the overall guidance and issuance process oversight. The members of the governance structure will develop the process and criteria guiding the selection of eligible projects funded by green bond proceeds and aligned with Peru’s NDC commitments and the 9 Priority Objectives in the National Competitiveness and Productivity Plan, which span all of the productive sectors (e.g. agriculture, manufacturing, energy and mining). The governance structure will guarantee broad government ownership of the decision-making processes on the selection of eligible projects and facilitate engagement (including capacity building efforts) and validation of deliverables and outputs. The network will be implemented through GGGI experts being embedded within the relevant ministries to facilitate regular communication and will be delivered through the following steps:
1) Assist MEF with support from MINAM to define the roles, responsibilities, and composition of the governance structure;
2) Support MINAM and MEF to define governance structure working procedures. This will include one formal meeting to define the structure as well as informal meetings and coordination;
3) Support the MEF and MINAM to formalise the establishment of the GB governance structure in accordance with Peru’s legal Framework. This will include a green bond webinar to formalise the governance structure as well as informal meeting.
